# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
overview:<p>The Matador was developed by Clan Steel Viper during the Golden Century era, with its introduction recorded in approximately 2846. A pre-OmniMech heavy design, the Matador was conceived as a devastating close-range combatant, purpose-built to engage enemy BattleMechs at short distances where its formidable array of weaponry could be brought to bear. The design reflected the Steel Vipers' philosophy of honing their martial assets alongside warrior skill development.</p><p>The Matador's deliberately intimidating silhouette, reminiscent of the Atlas and Gargoyle, serves as much a psychological weapon as the armaments it carries. While never produced in large numbers, the design earned a reputation as a brutal urban fighter among Clan forces, and its presence on a battlefield signaled that the Steel Vipers intended to close the distance and fight on their own terms.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Matador's design philosophy centers on overwhelming firepower at close range, backed by substantial protection. Massive angular armor plates give the sixty-ton 'Mech an imposing profile while twelve tons of Forging C629/j armor provide protection unrivaled among 'Mechs of comparable weight, ensuring the Matador can close to its preferred engagement distance despite concentrated enemy fire.</p><p>The weapon array reflects a clear close-combat doctrine. Four Series XII rotary machine guns mounted on each shoulder deliver devastating anti-infantry firepower, while Pattern J6 Streak SRM-6 and Pattern JX Streak SRM-4 launchers provide accurate missile support. A pair of Series 2b extended-range medium lasers in the left torso offer the Matador's only real reach beyond short range. Twin Chi Series small pulse lasers in the center torso complement three Lambda medium pulse lasers arranged in a triangular pattern within the heavily armored left arm, where shock-resistant housings keep them operational even after physical combat.</p><p>The Matador's top speed of sixty-five kilometers per hour is modest for a heavy 'Mech, but Pryzhok WM 10 jump jets provide a hundred and twenty meters of jump capability, granting crucial maneuverability in the close terrain where it excels. Heat management requires careful attention from the MechWarrior, though the restrictive environments favoring the design typically offer opportunities to disengage and cool down between engagements.</p>

deployment:<p>The standard Matador served as a mainstay of Clan Steel Viper second-line formations for centuries, fielded primarily in garrison Clusters and used extensively in inter-Clan Trials where close-quarters combat was expected. The base configuration's reliance on short-range weaponry made it a natural choice for planetary garrison duty, where urban environments and defensive positions favored its design philosophy. Steel Viper commanders frequently deployed Matadors in pairs or Stars alongside faster screening elements that could herd opponents into the close engagements where the design excelled.</p>

history:<p>The Matador has served the Clan Steel Viper touman since its introduction in the mid-twenty-ninth century, seeing extensive combat across centuries of inter-Clan rivalry and Trials. Produced at the Novy Minsk Armaments Plant on New Kent, the design was actively manufactured through the Late Succession Wars era before production slowed as the Steel Vipers redirected resources toward newer designs and OmniMech development during the Clan Invasion period.</p><p>Despite being relegated to second-line duties by the late thirty-first century, the Matador demonstrated its continued combat value during the Harvest Wars. When Wolf Khan Vladimir Ward targeted several Steel Viper units equipped with the design, those forces held their own against the Wolf aggressors. Elements of the Steel Vipers' Sixty-first Striker Cluster, operating as part of the Homeworlds-based Steel Coil Galaxy, issued a preemptive batchall to the Wolf forces. Though this engagement ultimately led to the defection of nearly a full Trinary of Steel Vipers to Clan Wolf, the Matador-equipped warriors performed admirably against their opponents.</p><p>The design never spread far beyond the Steel Vipers, who never actively traded the Matador. Fewer than two dozen examples existed outside the Clan throughout its production history, though scattered examples were captured by Clan Jade Falcon, Clan Star Adder, and Clan Fire Mandrill through various Trials over the centuries.</p><p>The Steel Vipers' destruction during the Wars of Reaving in the late 3070s scattered surviving Matadors among the remaining Homeworld Clans. The Jade Falcons, having acquired several through their battles with the Vipers, initially relegated them to provisional garrison Clusters and solahma units despite the stigma associated with a Steel Viper design. Several were reassigned to sibkos for use in Trials of Position. The development of a field refit variant on Chahar during the Jihad era represented an effort to rehabilitate the design's reputation while adapting it to Jade Falcon tactical doctrine, replacing the original close-combat loadout with advanced tactical missiles and heavy lasers better suited to Falcon combat philosophy.</p>

